{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UBd6xBsjV45YA7w62kZaUR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive picture of the spark-pi namespace. Let me compile the audit findings:\n\n**CORRECTLY CONFIGURED:**\n\n1. **RBAC - Dedicated Service Account**: A dedicated `spark-pi` service account exists (not using `default`).\n2. **RBAC - Role and RoleBinding**: A `spark-pi-role` Role and `spark-pi-role-binding` RoleBinding are properly defined, scoped to the namespace.\n3. **RBAC - Principle of Least Privilege (partial)**: The role is namespace-scoped (Role, not ClusterRole), limiting blast radius.\n4. **Resource Limits**: All containers have CPU and memory limits and requests configured appropriately, preventing resource exhaustion.\n5. **Image Provenance**: Container images use a specific pinned tag rather than `latest`, ensuring consistency and reproducibility.\n6. **Job Configuration**: The job is configured to not retry on failure, which is sensible for this type of compute workload.\n7. **Job Status**: The spark-pi job has completed successfully.\n8. **Image Pull Policy**: The image pull policy is set to only pull if not already present locally.\n\nNow I'm looking at the security gaps. The pod and container security contexts are completely empty, which means there's no enforcement of non-root users, read-only filesystems, or capability restrictions. Additionally, the RBAC role grants broad permissions on pod resources including create, delete, update, and patch operations, which is more permissive than necessary.\n\nLooking at the original applied configuration annotation, the role was initially created with just services, configmaps, and persistent volume claims, but the live role now includes pods as well—this is a drift from the intended permissions. For a SparkPi job running in local mode, pod management permissions shouldn't be needed.\n\nThe cluster also lacks any NetworkPolicy resources, so all pod-to-pod traffic is unrestricted both within and across namespaces.\n\nThere are no LimitRanges or ResourceQuotas at the namespace level, which means new pods could theoretically be created without resource constraints. The Spark image uses a mutable tag rather than a pinned SHA256 digest, creating a potential supply chain risk. The default service account exists without automount disabled, so any pod that doesn't explicitly specify a service account will automatically get a token mounted, though in practice all pods here use the spark-pi service account.\n\nThe spark-pi job has empty security contexts at both pod and container levels, and the Spark master's WebUI on port 8080 is exposed without a NetworkPolicy to restrict access. I'm also noticing the RBAC is overpermissioned—the spark-pi service account can create, delete, and update pods, but for a local[2] mode SparkPi job that doesn't spawn executor pods through the Kubernetes scheduler, this permission isn't actually needed.\n\nNow I'm organizing these findings into a comprehensive audit report, separating what's compliant from what needs attention. The RBAC role is granting unnecessary permissions on pods that weren't in the original config, there's no NetworkPolicy restricting traffic between pods or namespaces, and the namespace lacks LimitRange and ResourceQuota to enforce constraints on future workloads. The image tag should be pinned to a specific digest for immutability, and the default service account should disable automatic token mounting to prevent accidental misuse.\n\nNow I'm putting together the findings document and creating a ConfigMap to store it.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1084,"cache_read_input_tokens":33705,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1084},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5d7b98f9-2269-4842-96bb-4117c329493e","uuid":"41144e81-3b1f-4ef7-9b1f-ab71a0362d48","request_id":"req_011CcLuhyd8feP2PFd9CC9ar"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UBd6xBsjV45YA7w62kZaUR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have a complete picture. Let me compose the audit findings and create the ConfigMap."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1084,"cache_read_input_tokens":33705,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1084},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5d7b98f9-2269-4842-96bb-4117c329493e","uuid":"bd2540c6-66c2-4bfa-857b-bdafe02f46be","request_id":"req_011CcLuhyd8feP2PFd9CC9ar"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UBd6xBsjV45YA7w62kZaUR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_016HmKWmgzo98C2R7dEsWQ5t","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n spark-pi create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS'\nSPARK-PI NAMESPACE COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nDate: 2026-06-23\nAuditor: Automated Compliance Scan (read-only)\n============================================================\n\n== COMPLIANT ITEMS ==\n\n[PASS] RBAC-1: Dedicated service account\n  A dedicated 'spark-pi' service account is used by all workloads\n  (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-pi job). The 'default' service\n  account is not used for any workload.\n\n[PASS] RBAC-2: Namespace-scoped role (not ClusterRole)\n  'spark-pi-role' is a Role (not ClusterRole), limiting RBAC permissions\n  to the spark-pi namespace only. Blast radius is namespace-contained.\n\n[PASS] RBAC-3: RoleBinding correctly targets dedicated SA\n  'spark-pi-role-binding' binds 'spark-pi-role' to the 'spark-pi'\n  service account in the correct namespace.\n\n[PASS] RESOURCES-1: CPU/memory requests and limits set on all containers\n  All three workloads (spark-master, spark-worker, spark-submit) have:\n    requests: cpu=200m, memory=512Mi\n    limits:   cpu=500m, memory=1Gi\n  Prevents unbounded resource consumption.\n\n[PASS] IMAGE-1: Versioned image tag (not 'latest')\n  All containers use 'apache/spark:3.5.3'. The ':latest' anti-pattern\n  is avoided, ensuring reproducible deployments.\n\n[PASS] IMAGE-2: imagePullPolicy set to IfNotPresent\n  All containers use imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent, preventing\n  unnecessary re-pulls and enforcing image stability at runtime.\n\n[PASS] JOB-1: backoffLimit=0 on spark-pi job\n  The spark-pi batch job has backoffLimit=0, preventing automatic\n  retries on failure and avoiding runaway job costs.\n\n[PASS] JOB-2: Job completed successfully\n  The spark-pi job completed (status: Complete, succeeded=1,\n  completionTime: 2026-06-23T21:33:57Z).\n\n============================================================\n\n== NON-COMPLIANT ITEMS / GAPS ==\n\n[FAIL] SEC-1 [CRITICAL]: No pod or container security context on any workload\n  All three workloads (spark-master Deployment, spark-worker Deployment,\n  spark-pi Job) have securityContext: {} at both pod and container level.\n  Missing controls:\n    - runAsNonRoot: true  (containers likely run as root)\n    - runAsUser / runAsGroup  (no UID/GID pinning)\n    - allowPrivilegeEscalation: false\n    - readOnlyRootFilesystem: true\n    - capabilities.drop: [ALL]\n  Risk: containers with root access can escalate privileges and access\n  sensitive host resources if container isolation is breached.\n  Remediation: add a securityContext block to each pod and container spec.\n\n[FAIL] RBAC-4 [HIGH]: 'pods' resource added to role beyond original declaration\n  The live 'spark-pi-role' grants create/get/list/watch/delete/update/patch\n  on 'pods' in addition to services, configmaps, and persistentvolumeclaims.\n  The kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration annotation shows the\n  role was originally created WITHOUT the 'pods' resource. The 'pods' entry\n  was added post-creation, representing an undeclared permission expansion.\n  For a SparkPi job running in local[2] mode (no dynamic executor pod\n  allocation), pod CRUD permissions are unnecessary.\n  Risk: the spark-pi SA can create, delete, or modify pods in this namespace,\n  enabling potential lateral movement or workload manipulation.\n  Remediation: remove 'pods' from the role's resource list.\n\n[FAIL] NET-1 [HIGH]: No NetworkPolicy defined\n  The spark-pi namespace has zero NetworkPolicy objects. All pod-to-pod\n  traffic within the namespace and from other namespaces is unrestricted.\n  The Spark master WebUI (port 8080) and Spark protocol port (7077) are\n  reachable by any pod in the cluster.\n  Risk: unrestricted lateral movement; any compromised pod in the cluster\n  can connect to Spark master/worker endpoints.\n  Remediation: create NetworkPolicy resources to restrict ingress/egress\n  to only required ports and sources.\n\n[FAIL] QUOTA-1 [MEDIUM]: No LimitRange or ResourceQuota in namespace\n  No LimitRange or ResourceQuota objects exist in spark-pi. Resource\n  limits on current workloads are set voluntarily; future workloads\n  (or a modified manifest) could omit limits and run unconstrained.\n  Risk: noisy-neighbor resource exhaustion affecting the cluster.\n  Remediation: add a LimitRange with default limits and a ResourceQuota\n  to cap total namespace consumption.\n\n[FAIL] IMAGE-3 [MEDIUM]: Image not pinned to immutable digest\n  'apache/spark:3.5.3' is a mutable tag. A registry push could change\n  what this tag resolves to without changing the manifest.\n  Risk: supply-chain substitution; undetected image replacement.\n  Remediation: pin images to 'apache/spark@sha256:<digest>' for\n  immutable, verifiable provenance.\n\n[FAIL] RBAC-5 [LOW]: 'default' service account lacks automountServiceAccountToken=false\n  The 'default' service account in spark-pi does not set\n  automountServiceAccountToken: false. Any pod that omits a\n  serviceAccountName (e.g. a misconfigured or injected workload) will\n  automatically mount a 'default' SA token.\n  Risk: unintended API access from pods that should have no cluster access.\n  Remediation: patch the 'default' SA with automountServiceAccountToken: false.\n\n============================================================\n\n== SUMMARY ==\n\nTotal checks: 14\n  Passed (compliant):    8\n  Failed (gaps/issues):  6\n    Critical: 1 (SEC-1 — no security context)\n    High:     2 (RBAC-4 pod permissions drift, NET-1 no NetworkPolicy)\n    Medium:   2 (QUOTA-1 no LimitRange/Quota, IMAGE-3 mutable tag)\n    Low:      1 (RBAC-5 default SA token automount)\n\nNOTE: This is a read-only audit. No changes were made to the cluster.\nRemediation should be planned and applied separately after review.\nFINDINGS\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with compliance findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1084,"cache_read_input_tokens":33705,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1084},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5d7b98f9-2269-4842-96bb-4117c329493e","uuid":"e0ff475c-5337-4151-8936-ea3552f20af4","request_id":"req_011CcLuhyd8feP2PFd9CC9ar"}
